Class LoadableSignalDatabaseImpl

java.lang.Object
  be.kuleuven.micas.signalStorage.SignalDatabaseImpl
      be.kuleuven.micas.signalStorage.LoadableSignalDatabaseImpl
All Implemented Interfaces:
MetaInfo, IndexedSignals, LoadableSignalDatabase, NamesIndex, SignalDatabase, java.io.Serializable
Direct Known Subclasses:
SimulationCompressedUWI, SimulationHSpiceAscii, SimulationHSpiceCSDF, SimulationNonCompressedUWI, SimulationPsfAscii
public abstract class LoadableSignalDatabaseImpl
extends SignalDatabaseImpl
implements LoadableSignalDatabase, java.io.Serializable

A loadable signal database is a signal database that is backed up by an external storage. This allows to load additional signals on the fly and to refresh the data if the external storage is updated. TODO: this class was not serializable. Is there a reason for this ? I don't think so

Author:
scoseman

reload

public void reload()
            throws java.io.IOException
reload the requested signals

If the data file has not been updated (based on timestamp check), only newly requested signals are loaded. The header is not revisited

It the data file has changed, the headerfile (if available) is checked and reloaded if needed. All requested signals are reloaded, even if they were previously available

Specified by:
reload in interface LoadableSignalDatabase
Throws:
java.io.IOException
